aurs, Ayrshire, Scotland","Glencairn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Glencairn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Riddell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: variant of   Riddle  . A family of the name <i>Riddell</i> has been established in Whitton in Roxburghshire since the mid 12th century, when Walter <i>de Riddel</i>, from Rydale (North Yorkshire), settled in Scotland after accompanying King David. Another unrelated family of this name have been established in Northumberland since at least the 14th century, with William <i>de Ridell</i> having been sheriff of the county in 1314."],"variants":[{"name":"Riddle","meanings":["English:","habitational name probably chiefly from Ryedale, a river valley in North Yorkshire. The placename derives from the river name <i>Rye</i> (of uncertain etymology) + Old Norse <i>dalr</i> ‘valley’. There are, however, other places called Rydale (in Westmorland for example) which could have given rise to hereditary surnames.","of Norman origin, from an Old French personal name <i>Ridel</i>, perhaps a pet form of ancient Germanic names such as <i>Ridbald</i> and <i>Ridhari(us)</i>."]},{"name":"Ridall","meanings":["Scottish and English (Yorkshire and Lincolnshire): variant of   Riddell  ."]},{"name":"Riddel","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Riddell  ; see   Riddle  ."]},{"name":"Rydell","meanings":["Swedish: ornamental name composed of the placename element <i>ryd</i> ‘woodland clearing’ + the suffix <i>-ell</i>, a derivative of the Latin adjectival ending <i>-elius</i>.","English: variant of   Riddell  ; see   Riddle  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Isabella","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."],"variants":[{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabella Maud Riddell Heiress of Glengarnock was born in 1207, in Glencairn, Dumfriesshire, Scotland as the daughter of Glengarnock Riddell. She married Sir Hervius \" Hervy Henry                \" de Cunynghame in 1223, in Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1285, in Trabzon, Trabzon, Ottoman Empire, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1207–1285":"1207–1285","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1223–1285":"1223–1285","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","25 December 1223":"25. detsember 1223","1205":"1205","1223":"1223","1264":"1264","1285":"1285","1185":"1185","1207":"1207","Trabzon, Trabzon, Ottoman Empire":"Trabzo